~ Chapter 2 — attention as labour, the Arendt-Weil overlay.

reference ../shared/schema.wit
reference ../shared/sources.wit

+#bibliography: @entry Arendt, Hannah (1958). The Human Condition. University of Chicago Press. entry@

#chapter_two
@chapter |number 2| |title Attention and Labour|

@section |title Arendt on labour|

@arendt_labour distinguishes labour from work and action: labour
is what sustains the species, what must be done again the next
day, what leaves no monument. Most of human life, on this view,
is labour. The trouble is that attention has been written out of
this account — Arendt's _labour_ is bodily, agricultural, the
keeping-alive of bodies. But the keeping-alive of meanings is
also labour, and it, too, must be done again the next day.

@section |title Weil on the cost of looking|

Weil's intuition is that the cost is moral as well as cognitive.
To attend, @weil_generosity argues, is to suspend the self — to
hold the object as an _it_ rather than as material for one's own
projects. Most of us cannot sustain this for more than a minute
at a time. The minute is precious.

@section |title The asymmetric ledger|

@theorem |number 1| |statement Attention is asymmetrically distributed across the social field, and the distribution tracks power.|

It does not follow that this is novel. It follows only that, if
the labour reading is correct, the politics of attention is not a
luxury topic — it is what most of our moral life consists in.

